1
00:00:00,976 --> 00:00:03,317
{\an8}[JUGHEAD] <i>For years,
Riverdale had prided itself</i>

2
00:00:03,400 --> 00:00:05,156
{\an8}<i>as being the Town With Pep.</i>

3
00:00:05,239 --> 00:00:07,748
{\an8}<i>Safe. Innocent. Utopian.</i>

4
00:00:07,831 --> 00:00:09,837
<i>- But after recent events...</i>
- [TYPEWRITER CLICKING]

5
00:00:09,921 --> 00:00:13,473
<i>...there was no denying the darkness
that churned beneath Riverdale.</i>

6
00:00:13,557 --> 00:00:17,193
<i>The inequality, the prejudice,
the fearmongering.</i>

7
00:00:17,736 --> 00:00:23,295
<i>It had been bubbling to the surface
and very nearly exploded.</i>

8
00:00:23,379 --> 00:00:26,262
<i>Now a reshuffling was happening.</i>

9
00:00:26,346 --> 00:00:28,184
{\an8}[SINISTER MUSIC PLAYING]

10
00:00:28,269 --> 00:00:31,904
{\an8}<i>Now some new way of thinking,
of being, was required.</i>

11
00:00:33,033 --> 00:00:36,837
<i>Principal Featherhead
was stepping down from his cherished post.</i>

12
00:00:37,589 --> 00:00:41,517
<i>The official story was...
"for personal reasons."</i>

13
00:00:42,479 --> 00:00:43,524
<i>But word from the bird</i>

14
00:00:43,608 --> 00:00:46,617
<i>was that he'd been identified
by an anonymous accuser</i>

15
00:00:46,700 --> 00:00:50,670
<i>as an accessory
to Mayor Blossom's Soviet shenanigans.</i>

16
00:00:52,802 --> 00:00:55,269
[HAL] With the sudden vacancy
in the principal's office,

17
00:00:55,353 --> 00:00:59,615
the PTA is initiating a county-wide search
for a replacement.

18
00:00:59,698 --> 00:01:03,168
- Mm.
- Here's hoping this one makes the grade.

19
00:01:03,251 --> 00:01:04,087
Yes.

20
00:01:04,170 --> 00:01:07,013
[JUGHEAD] <i>In light of recent revelations
and after much discussion,</i>

21
00:01:07,097 --> 00:01:10,650
<i>Mr. and Mrs. Cooper had decided
to continue living on Elm Street</i>

22
00:01:10,733 --> 00:01:12,113
<i>as husband and wife.</i>

23
00:01:12,196 --> 00:01:16,000
<i>Though Mr. Cooper would be moving
into the basement bedroom.</i>

24
00:01:17,671 --> 00:01:21,433
<i>A decision that...
frankly, flummoxed Betty.</i>

25
00:01:26,029 --> 00:01:27,702
[ALICE] You know the truth now, Betty.

26
00:01:27,785 --> 00:01:30,209
Why didn't you leave Dad back then?

27
00:01:30,293 --> 00:01:33,093
When you first learned about his affair
with Mrs. Muggs?

28
00:01:34,221 --> 00:01:38,359
I didn't wanna break up our family
over his indiscretions.

29
00:01:39,404 --> 00:01:41,787
I didn't want you and Polly
to grow up without a father.

30
00:01:41,870 --> 00:01:44,295
Well, why don't you divorce Dad now?

31
00:01:46,134 --> 00:01:50,523
What am I gonna do? My life
is so intertwined with your father's.

32
00:01:50,606 --> 00:01:51,777
This is his house.

33
00:01:52,695 --> 00:01:56,249
I don't own the station. I can't even
open a bank account of my own.

34
00:01:58,881 --> 00:01:59,884
And what a...?

35
00:02:00,678 --> 00:02:03,061
What about when you go off to college?

36
00:02:06,906 --> 00:02:08,452
I'm gonna be alone.

37
00:02:15,933 --> 00:02:17,564
You know that I have...

38
00:02:18,442 --> 00:02:20,448
never been alone a day in my life?

39
00:02:20,531 --> 00:02:26,132
I lived in my parents' house
until the day that I married your father.

40
00:02:38,336 --> 00:02:41,388
[NANA] It's just the three
of us now, children.

41
00:02:42,139 --> 00:02:47,489
May your idiot father and viper mother
both rot in a Russian gulag

42
00:02:47,572 --> 00:02:50,080
for the rest of their miserable lives.

43
00:02:50,164 --> 00:02:52,672
From your lips to Moloch's ears, Nana.

44
00:02:52,756 --> 00:02:55,597
I always knew there was
something squirrelly about Mom and Dad.

45
00:02:55,681 --> 00:02:58,607
In the meanwhile, it's up to us

46
00:02:58,691 --> 00:03:03,288
to ensure that the Blossoms rise
from the ashes like phoenixes.

47
00:03:03,371 --> 00:03:05,127
I wholeheartedly concur.

48
00:03:05,210 --> 00:03:10,435
And, rest assured, I know exactly
what my first order of business will be.

49
00:03:11,313 --> 00:03:12,650
[SCHOOL BELL RINGS]

50
00:03:12,734 --> 00:03:15,911
So, with Featherhead gone,
who's gonna run the asylum now?

51
00:03:15,994 --> 00:03:20,090
Well, not to sound like Chicken Little,
but... what if it's Dr. Werthers?

52
00:03:20,842 --> 00:03:22,807
There's gotta be
better candidates out there.

53
00:03:22,890 --> 00:03:23,976
Like Captain Hook?

54
00:03:24,687 --> 00:03:25,690
Or Godzilla?

55
00:03:26,192 --> 00:03:28,700
Just so long
as they don't ask my uncle to step up.

56
00:03:28,784 --> 00:03:30,288
I actually know the perfect candidate,

57
00:03:30,372 --> 00:03:32,879
but we would need support
from the PTA to push it through.

58
00:03:32,963 --> 00:03:34,927
My mom's president of the PTA, of course.

59
00:03:35,010 --> 00:03:36,014
Well, that's a brick wall.

60
00:03:36,098 --> 00:03:39,023
The last time we appealed to
your mom's better angels, she let us down.

61
00:03:39,107 --> 00:03:42,617
She did, but I think that we should
give her another chance.

62
00:03:42,701 --> 00:03:44,582
A lot has changed for her since then.

63
00:03:45,502 --> 00:03:49,431
Well, in the meantime, I'm going to pay
a house call on good old Dr. Moldy.

64
00:03:55,491 --> 00:03:58,249
Oh, I knew it.
Featherhead is barely out the door

65
00:03:58,333 --> 00:04:00,046
and you're already
trying to take his office?

66
00:04:00,129 --> 00:04:03,056
So, what's the plan?
Are you going to study us like lab rats

67
00:04:03,139 --> 00:04:05,940
or experiment on us
like some two-bit Dr. Moreau?

68
00:04:06,023 --> 00:04:10,704
Alas, Mr. Jones, I have no interest
in being principal of this school.

69
00:04:10,788 --> 00:04:13,420
No, I'm off to do real work in Washington.

70
00:04:13,504 --> 00:04:15,468
I'll be serving
on the president's subcommittee

71
00:04:15,553 --> 00:04:18,311
looking into the causes
of juvenile delinquency.

72
00:04:18,395 --> 00:04:21,863
Specifically its links
to comic books and other...

73
00:04:21,947 --> 00:04:24,538
subversive forms of popular culture.

74
00:04:24,622 --> 00:04:28,049
Well, golly.
Don't let the door hit you on the way out.

75
00:04:28,133 --> 00:04:29,637
Oh, fear not, though.

76
00:04:30,599 --> 00:04:34,319
My tribunal will still be doing the
important work of regulating comic books.

77
00:04:34,402 --> 00:04:36,994
- Censoring them, you mean.
- As a matter of fact,

78
00:04:37,077 --> 00:04:40,463
here is our response to your latest issue.

79
00:04:40,546 --> 00:04:43,555
Which we rejected,
for the reasons outlined herein.

80
00:04:43,639 --> 00:04:47,567
Good luck to you
and your colleagues at Pep Comics.

81
00:04:47,651 --> 00:04:49,573
While it still exists.

82
00:04:58,476 --> 00:05:00,525
Damn, Red. You still got it.

83
00:05:00,608 --> 00:05:01,569
I'm just buzzing, Reg.

84
00:05:01,653 --> 00:05:02,656
Buzzing.

85
00:05:02,739 --> 00:05:05,540
Earlier this week,
Mrs. Grundy told us to read <i>On the Road</i>

86
00:05:05,623 --> 00:05:08,047
by king of the Beats, Jack Kerouac.

87
00:05:08,632 --> 00:05:10,555
Brought everything into focus for me.

88
00:05:14,609 --> 00:05:17,117
"I was surprised, as always,

89
00:05:17,660 --> 00:05:19,917
by how easy the act of leaving was.

90
00:05:20,001 --> 00:05:21,213
And how good it felt.

91
00:05:21,757 --> 00:05:24,599
The world was suddenly rich
with possibility."

92
00:05:27,649 --> 00:05:30,283
- You really got the bug, huh?
- Yeah, I guess I do, Reg.

93
00:05:30,366 --> 00:05:34,295
So much so that this summer
I'm gonna ride the rails. Hit the trails.

94
00:05:34,378 --> 00:05:35,884
I'm gonna be a vagabond writer.

95
00:05:35,967 --> 00:05:40,271
Hop trains, explore the country,
sleep under the stars,

96
00:05:40,356 --> 00:05:43,574
and then write about my experiences,
wherever they may take me.

97
00:05:43,658 --> 00:05:46,876
- And what's your mom gonna say about that?
- My mom can't say diddly-squat,

98
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:48,757
'cause I'm doing this
during summer vacation.

99
00:05:49,425 --> 00:05:50,427
Well...

100
00:05:51,055 --> 00:05:54,399
jumping trains doesn't beat going
to the best basketball camp in the world,

101
00:05:54,483 --> 00:05:58,328
but if it floats your boat,
good on you, Arch.

102
00:06:03,009 --> 00:06:08,610
So, as a parting gift, Dr. Werthers
rejected <i>Zip Comics</i> Number 42?

103
00:06:09,110 --> 00:06:10,824
And what was his rationale, may I ask?

104
00:06:10,907 --> 00:06:13,666
Well, it's gotta be because
of the last story in that issue.

105
00:06:13,751 --> 00:06:15,087
- "The Comet."
- What?

106
00:06:15,882 --> 00:06:18,389
- But that one's the cat's pajamas.
- I know.

107
00:06:18,473 --> 00:06:20,939
It's based off a W.E.B. Du Bois story

108
00:06:21,023 --> 00:06:23,781
that Tabitha clued me into
last time she was in town.

109
00:06:23,864 --> 00:06:25,703
It's so romantic and philosophical.

110
00:06:26,413 --> 00:06:28,963
After a comet hits
and destroys New York City,

111
00:06:29,047 --> 00:06:31,722
a man and a woman come together
and fall in love.

112
00:06:31,806 --> 00:06:34,899
Their problem is that it's a Black man
and a white woman who find each other.

113
00:06:36,195 --> 00:06:39,831
I haven't even told Mr. Fieldstone yet.
I think it's gonna crush him.

114
00:06:39,914 --> 00:06:40,917
I'm sure.

115
00:06:41,419 --> 00:06:44,302
That "Comet" story is a masterpiece.

116
00:06:44,386 --> 00:06:46,768
Honestly, my first thought
when I read it was,

117
00:06:46,852 --> 00:06:49,109
"This would make for a fantabulous movie."

118
00:06:49,192 --> 00:06:50,112
Well...

119
00:06:50,990 --> 00:06:53,497
if anyone wants to get in touch
with Du Bois' representatives,

120
00:06:53,582 --> 00:06:55,295
I have all their information.

121
00:06:55,378 --> 00:06:57,385
[LIVELY, PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING]

122
00:06:58,387 --> 00:06:59,600
Just saying.

123
00:07:05,117 --> 00:07:08,711
Mom. This is your chance
to do the right thing.

124
00:07:08,795 --> 00:07:12,264
To make up for sitting on your hands
when I asked you to report on Emmett Till.

125
00:07:12,348 --> 00:07:14,019
I know you regret that.

126
00:07:14,104 --> 00:07:15,022
Mrs. Cooper,

127
00:07:15,732 --> 00:07:17,864
when Riverdale High integrated,

128
00:07:17,949 --> 00:07:20,706
three of the Black schools
in town shut down.

129
00:07:20,790 --> 00:07:24,175
And suddenly dozens of great teachers
were kicked to the curb.

130
00:07:24,927 --> 00:07:29,233
There's this incredible educator
who spent the last year driving a cab...

131
00:07:29,316 --> 00:07:33,120
Girls, I would love to help,
but the rest of the PTA...

132
00:07:33,203 --> 00:07:34,373
Mom.

133
00:07:34,456 --> 00:07:36,129
Make them understand.

134
00:07:36,212 --> 00:07:40,392
Riverdale is at a turning point.
Now is the time for a fresh start.

135
00:07:40,476 --> 00:07:42,399
[PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING]

136
00:07:44,822 --> 00:07:47,246
[CROWD APPLAUDING, CHEERING]

137
00:07:48,835 --> 00:07:49,879
[ALICE CHUCKLES]

138
00:07:54,060 --> 00:07:56,107
[CROWD WHISTLING]

139
00:07:56,191 --> 00:07:57,319
Morning, students.

140
00:07:58,197 --> 00:08:00,161
I know you've all had a difficult year.

141
00:08:00,704 --> 00:08:02,752
I know your previous principal...

142
00:08:03,965 --> 00:08:08,897
wasn't exactly open to change,
to new ideas,

143
00:08:09,482 --> 00:08:12,742
to addressing the needs
of all his students.

144
00:08:12,826 --> 00:08:13,954
Well...

145
00:08:15,625 --> 00:08:17,716
let me make one thing clear.

146
00:08:19,930 --> 00:08:23,400
I'm here... for every student.

147
00:08:25,781 --> 00:08:26,744
That said...

148
00:08:28,415 --> 00:08:32,803
the challenges that face us
are enormous and systemic,

149
00:08:32,887 --> 00:08:37,108
and if you're not part of the solution,
then you're part of the problem.

150
00:08:38,446 --> 00:08:39,784
{\an8}So I challenge you all:

151
00:08:41,998 --> 00:08:43,002
Be kind.

152
00:08:44,966 --> 00:08:46,011
Be decent.

153
00:08:47,850 --> 00:08:49,438
{\an8}Be better.

154
00:08:52,280 --> 00:08:53,576
Now, let's get to work!

155
00:08:54,788 --> 00:08:56,837
[CROWD CHEERING]

156
00:08:56,920 --> 00:08:58,926
[STIRRING MUSIC PLAYING]

157
00:09:25,759 --> 00:09:27,598
- [ARCHIE] Principal Weatherbee?
- Yes.

158
00:09:28,433 --> 00:09:30,189
Hi. I'm Archie. Archie Andrews.

159
00:09:30,272 --> 00:09:31,442
Please, sit.

160
00:09:34,703 --> 00:09:36,458
{\an8}What can I do for you, Mr. Andrews?

161
00:09:36,542 --> 00:09:40,638
{\an8}Well, there used to be a teacher
who worked here, a real top-notch teach.

162
00:09:41,431 --> 00:09:44,023
{\an8}She was falsely accused
of being a Communist,

163
00:09:44,107 --> 00:09:45,528
and she was fired for it.

164
00:09:46,029 --> 00:09:49,331
- Her name's Mrs. Thornton.
- I know Edith Thornton very well.

165
00:09:49,415 --> 00:09:51,463
She is a wonderful educator.

166
00:09:51,547 --> 00:09:53,720
{\an8}I know.
Well, that's why I was hoping that...

167
00:09:53,803 --> 00:09:56,185
{\an8}Let me see if I can't right this wrong.

168
00:09:56,980 --> 00:09:58,191
{\an8}Get Edith back here.

169
00:09:58,777 --> 00:10:00,616
{\an8}Well, that would be swell,
Principal Weatherbee.

170
00:10:00,700 --> 00:10:02,706
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

171
00:10:08,892 --> 00:10:10,898
[SUAVE MUSIC PLAYING]

172
00:10:13,823 --> 00:10:16,749
{\an8}Hold on to your pom-poms,
my beloved paper-shakers,

173
00:10:16,832 --> 00:10:18,505
{\an8}because I'm back!

174
00:10:18,588 --> 00:10:20,887
{\an8}Cheryl, this is a private practice
for Vixens,

175
00:10:20,970 --> 00:10:23,521
{\an8}not has-been daughters of Russian spies.

176
00:10:23,604 --> 00:10:27,324
{\an8}Now that Principal Weatherbee is ushering
in a new golden age at Riverdale High,

177
00:10:27,408 --> 00:10:30,917
{\an8}I am launching a coup
to take back control of my Vixens.

178
00:10:31,503 --> 00:10:35,683
{\an8}Therefore, Evelyn,
I am challenging you to a dance-off.

179
00:10:35,766 --> 00:10:36,937
Winner takes all.

180
00:10:37,020 --> 00:10:38,901
- I refuse your challenge.
- [SCOFFS]

181
00:10:40,070 --> 00:10:42,161
{\an8}["ROCKIN' ROBIN" PLAYING ON STEREO]

182
00:10:42,244 --> 00:10:45,253
{\an8}<i>♪ The pretty little raven
At the bird bandstand... ♪</i>

183
00:10:45,337 --> 00:10:47,176
{\an8}That's not an option.

184
00:10:48,054 --> 00:10:50,645
{\an8}<i>♪ They started going steady
And bless my soul ♪</i>

185
00:10:50,729 --> 00:10:53,069
{\an8}<i>♪ He out-bopped the buzzard
And the oriole ♪</i>

186
00:10:53,153 --> 00:10:55,745
<i>♪ He rocks in the treetop all day long ♪</i>

187
00:10:55,828 --> 00:10:58,753
<i>♪ Hoppin' and a-boppin'
And a-singin' his song ♪</i>

188
00:10:58,837 --> 00:11:01,805
{\an8}<i>♪ All the little birds on Jaybird Street ♪</i>

189
00:11:01,888 --> 00:11:04,437
{\an8}<i>♪ Love to hear the robin go
"Tweet, tweet, tweet" ♪</i>

190
00:11:04,521 --> 00:11:07,322
<i>- ♪ Rockin' robin ♪
- ♪ Tweet, tweet, tweet ♪</i>

191
00:11:07,405 --> 00:11:10,288
<i>- ♪ Rockin' robin ♪
- ♪ Tweet, tweedle-lee-dee ♪</i>

192
00:11:10,373 --> 00:11:13,465
<i>♪ Blow, rockin' robin
'Cause we're really gonna rock tonight ♪</i>

193
00:11:13,550 --> 00:11:15,597
<i>♪ Tweet, tweedle-lee-dee ♪</i>

194
00:11:15,681 --> 00:11:18,606
{\an8}<i>♪ Tweedle-lee deedle-dee-dee
Tweedle-lee deedle-dee-dee ♪</i>

195
00:11:18,691 --> 00:11:21,574
{\an8}<i>♪ Tweedle-lee deedle-dee-dee
Tweedle-lee deedle-dee-dee ♪</i>

196
00:11:21,657 --> 00:11:23,831
<i>♪ Tweedle-lee deedle-dee-dee
Tweedle-lee deedle-dee-dee ♪</i>

197
00:11:23,914 --> 00:11:25,544
<i>♪ Tweet, tweet ♪</i>

198
00:11:36,912 --> 00:11:39,588
{\an8}[ARCH MUSIC PLAYING]

199
00:11:39,671 --> 00:11:40,716
Your turn.

200
00:11:47,528 --> 00:11:48,783
{\an8}[SCREAMS]

201
00:11:51,165 --> 00:11:52,503
{\an8}[DOOR OPENS]

202
00:11:52,586 --> 00:11:55,930
{\an8}Today marks the beginning
of a new era for the Vixens.

203
00:11:57,058 --> 00:11:58,187
{\an8}To that end...

204
00:11:59,565 --> 00:12:01,405
{\an8}I have decided to live in the light.

205
00:12:02,826 --> 00:12:04,373
{\an8}I'm going steady with Toni Topaz.

206
00:12:04,456 --> 00:12:06,169
And if anyone here
has a problem with that,

207
00:12:06,254 --> 00:12:10,224
{\an8}you are more than welcome to follow Evelyn
out that door and into a dumpster.

208
00:12:12,898 --> 00:12:14,821
{\an8}We're in full support of you, Cheryl.

209
00:12:14,904 --> 00:12:16,910
{\an8}And we also...

210
00:12:17,831 --> 00:12:19,377
{\an8}Want to live in the light.

211
00:12:19,461 --> 00:12:20,797
[CHEERLEADERS APPLAUDING]

212
00:12:27,026 --> 00:12:30,285
{\an8}[JUGHEAD] Mr. Fieldstone,
I'm sorry I didn't tell you sooner.

213
00:12:30,368 --> 00:12:32,249
I get it, kid. I get it.

214
00:12:34,047 --> 00:12:37,683
"Rejected for not promoting
traditional American values."

215
00:12:39,021 --> 00:12:40,692
You know what that's code for?

216
00:12:40,776 --> 00:12:45,625
They didn't wanna see a Black man
and a white woman end up together.

217
00:12:45,708 --> 00:12:47,924
- So, what do we do now?
- What do you mean?

218
00:12:49,134 --> 00:12:51,853
We publish without the damn seal.
That's what we do.

219
00:12:52,479 --> 00:12:54,317
Send it out in the world
and hope for the best.

220
00:12:54,402 --> 00:12:55,865
I was hoping you'd say that.

221
00:12:56,408 --> 00:12:59,166
And depending on the sales,
I was thinking next time we could...

222
00:12:59,250 --> 00:13:00,839
There's not gonna be a next time, kid.

223
00:13:02,050 --> 00:13:03,763
No, that's it for me. I'm done.

224
00:13:04,893 --> 00:13:08,863
I mean, this is the best comic
I ever put together.

225
00:13:08,946 --> 00:13:10,952
[GENTLE, EMOTIONAL MUSIC PLAYING]

226
00:13:11,037 --> 00:13:12,248
It's a work of art.

227
00:13:12,333 --> 00:13:14,004
I mean, it actually says something.

228
00:13:14,589 --> 00:13:17,180
And that tribunal couldn't care less.

229
00:13:17,263 --> 00:13:18,643
So let the comic...

230
00:13:19,395 --> 00:13:20,858
be Pep's swan song.

231
00:13:22,029 --> 00:13:23,910
I can't imagine a better one.

232
00:13:25,330 --> 00:13:26,501
In the meantime...

233
00:13:27,337 --> 00:13:28,924
would you do me a favor, kid?

234
00:13:31,516 --> 00:13:34,233
Would you write the last editorial?

235
00:13:34,775 --> 00:13:37,033
Think of it as our eulogy.

236
00:13:38,495 --> 00:13:40,795
For the final issue of Pep Comics.

237
00:13:42,173 --> 00:13:43,761
It's been an honor, kid.

238
00:13:46,646 --> 00:13:47,858
It really has.

239
00:13:51,786 --> 00:13:52,874
[FIELDSTONE SIGHS]

240
00:13:52,957 --> 00:13:54,587
Well... [CHUCKLES]

241
00:13:55,966 --> 00:13:58,390
It was a beautiful dream while it lasted.

242
00:14:05,872 --> 00:14:07,878
[MYSTERIOUS MUSIC PLAYING]

243
00:14:13,604 --> 00:14:16,237
Oh, my gosh. I've been waiting for this.

244
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:18,034
What did you get, hon?

245
00:14:21,879 --> 00:14:22,882
[BETTY EXHALES]

246
00:14:22,967 --> 00:14:25,140
It's the first copy of my book.

247
00:14:25,223 --> 00:14:26,519
You wrote a book?

248
00:14:27,062 --> 00:14:29,361
Your mom and dad
must be very proud of you.

249
00:14:35,003 --> 00:14:36,174
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

250
00:14:41,774 --> 00:14:43,279
Oh, hey, Kev.

251
00:14:43,362 --> 00:14:45,870
- What are you doing here?
- Audrey said you weren't feeling great,

252
00:14:45,953 --> 00:14:48,544
so I thought I'd bring you
some of Pop's chicken noodle.

253
00:14:48,629 --> 00:14:50,509
Oh. Well, I appreciate that. That's...

254
00:14:52,516 --> 00:14:53,727
That's great.

255
00:14:55,316 --> 00:14:56,654
[KEVIN] Coach Andrews?

256
00:14:57,489 --> 00:14:58,911
What's going on?

257
00:14:58,994 --> 00:15:02,087
Uh, I'm staying in the motel as well,
and, uh...

258
00:15:03,090 --> 00:15:06,726
the shower in my room is on the fritz,
so, you... Your dad let me use his.

259
00:15:06,810 --> 00:15:07,645
Yeah.

260
00:15:08,356 --> 00:15:09,610
Right.

261
00:15:09,694 --> 00:15:11,407
You wanna come in, grab a flop?

262
00:15:12,034 --> 00:15:14,625
Um, no. No, um...

263
00:15:15,629 --> 00:15:17,342
I should probably cut out.

264
00:15:30,550 --> 00:15:31,385
[BETTY] Mom?

265
00:15:32,012 --> 00:15:34,646
I have something that I wanna show you.

266
00:15:34,729 --> 00:15:35,607
Oh.

267
00:15:36,610 --> 00:15:37,529
What is it, Betty?

268
00:15:43,757 --> 00:15:45,512
I wrote a book.

269
00:15:50,110 --> 00:15:51,447
Goodness. Yes.

270
00:15:52,784 --> 00:15:55,544
You... You did.
I see that you're on the cover.

271
00:15:56,170 --> 00:15:57,633
In undergarments.

272
00:15:59,932 --> 00:16:02,105
I really, really want you to read it.

273
00:16:02,188 --> 00:16:06,661
Mm. It says right there in the title
it's for teenagers.

274
00:16:06,745 --> 00:16:08,039
I mean, why would I read it?

275
00:16:08,123 --> 00:16:09,754
Well, in an ideal world,

276
00:16:09,837 --> 00:16:12,972
I'd love for you to be proud of me
for writing a book.

277
00:16:14,059 --> 00:16:19,366
But I'll settle for you reading it
just... to get to know me better.

278
00:16:21,539 --> 00:16:26,012
And maybe by getting to know me better,
you might get to know yourself better.

279
00:16:32,031 --> 00:16:33,117
[CLEARS THROAT]

280
00:16:36,963 --> 00:16:39,512
[ARCHIE] <i>Oh, it is so great
to have you back, Mrs. Thornton.</i>

281
00:16:39,595 --> 00:16:42,689
Geraldine shared some
of your recent poems with me.

282
00:16:42,772 --> 00:16:44,778
I do hope you plan
to stick with your writing.

283
00:16:44,863 --> 00:16:45,990
Oh, I do.

284
00:16:46,073 --> 00:16:48,916
In fact, this summer,
I'm gonna hit the rails.

285
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:50,630
Like all the Beat writers do.

286
00:16:50,714 --> 00:16:52,845
I'm gonna see if I can get at least one...

287
00:16:52,928 --> 00:16:56,732
great big juicy
Allen Ginsberg-like poem out of it.

288
00:16:56,815 --> 00:16:58,571
Oh, that's wonderful.

289
00:16:58,654 --> 00:17:02,207
You'll see what the world
beyond Riverdale is like.

290
00:17:02,291 --> 00:17:03,962
It's exactly what you should be doing

291
00:17:04,046 --> 00:17:06,428
at this point
in your development as a poet.

292
00:17:13,325 --> 00:17:14,160
Clay?

293
00:17:15,539 --> 00:17:16,459
Tell me,

294
00:17:16,542 --> 00:17:18,926
have you ever read the story "The Comet"?

295
00:17:19,511 --> 00:17:21,517
Of course. Multiple times, in fact.

296
00:17:22,561 --> 00:17:23,564
I figured you would have.

297
00:17:24,652 --> 00:17:25,947
In that case,

298
00:17:26,030 --> 00:17:30,920
how would you feel about writing
and directing an adaptation of "The Comet"

299
00:17:31,004 --> 00:17:33,594
as a major motion picture?

300
00:17:34,682 --> 00:17:38,109
Is this a gag? I've actually been fiddling
with a screenplay version

301
00:17:38,193 --> 00:17:39,573
of "The Comet" for years.

302
00:17:39,656 --> 00:17:41,537
Well, thanks to Jughead,

303
00:17:41,620 --> 00:17:44,003
I connected with Du Bois' agents,

304
00:17:44,086 --> 00:17:47,806
and it turns out the movie rights
had been languishing for years.

305
00:17:47,890 --> 00:17:49,519
So I snapped them up.

306
00:17:49,603 --> 00:17:53,156
And I suspected
you'd be passionate about this.

307
00:17:53,239 --> 00:17:55,370
Veronica, I can't believe
what I'm hearing.

308
00:17:55,454 --> 00:17:57,878
It's going to be an uphill battle.

309
00:17:57,961 --> 00:18:02,894
But there are things we can do,
like get the right star attached.

310
00:18:03,479 --> 00:18:05,946
Someone like, say...

311
00:18:06,029 --> 00:18:07,868
[BOTH] Sidney Poitier.

312
00:18:07,952 --> 00:18:10,041
- Precisely.
- Can you get to him?

313
00:18:10,877 --> 00:18:15,014
I might not be able to get to him,
but we both know someone who can.

314
00:18:15,098 --> 00:18:16,352
Josie McCoy.

315
00:18:16,937 --> 00:18:18,316
But, Clay...

316
00:18:18,400 --> 00:18:22,036
if we're going to attach
a big star like Sidney,

317
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:25,798
your adaptation needs to be undeniable.

318
00:18:25,882 --> 00:18:27,219
Don't worry. It will be.

319
00:18:27,303 --> 00:18:30,060
And who needs to wait for summer?
I'll get going right away.

320
00:18:30,145 --> 00:18:31,148
Wonderful.

321
00:18:33,447 --> 00:18:36,247
In that case,
I'm thinking a premiere at Cannes

322
00:18:36,331 --> 00:18:38,880
in the next four to five years.

323
00:18:38,963 --> 00:18:39,925
How does that sound?

324
00:18:47,658 --> 00:18:48,953
[VERONICA SQUEALS]

325
00:18:54,887 --> 00:18:55,765
Hey.

326
00:18:56,518 --> 00:18:58,565
- Why the long face?
- [SNIFFLES]

327
00:18:59,110 --> 00:19:01,951
I just got the information packet
for Camp Evans.

328
00:19:03,540 --> 00:19:05,086
My basketball camp.

329
00:19:06,967 --> 00:19:07,802
Well...

330
00:19:08,513 --> 00:19:10,352
Well, that's great, isn't it?

331
00:19:10,436 --> 00:19:12,400
Turns out they flip-flopped
the dates on me,

332
00:19:12,483 --> 00:19:14,449
and now it's smack-dab in the middle

333
00:19:14,532 --> 00:19:16,747
of our annual sweet-corn harvest
back on the farm.

334
00:19:16,830 --> 00:19:18,962
Well, can't you skip the harvest
this one time?

335
00:19:19,046 --> 00:19:20,968
The corn we harvest

336
00:19:21,553 --> 00:19:24,813
that single month supports our farm
for the rest of the year.

337
00:19:25,858 --> 00:19:27,364
There's no way I can miss it.

338
00:19:28,532 --> 00:19:29,703
My parents need me.

339
00:19:30,498 --> 00:19:34,426
So I just...
I gotta forget about basketball camp.

340
00:19:36,265 --> 00:19:37,394
[SNIFFLES]

341
00:19:38,104 --> 00:19:39,191
Well... [SCOFFS]

342
00:19:39,943 --> 00:19:41,114
...the heck with that.

343
00:19:42,953 --> 00:19:43,830
No.

344
00:19:44,582 --> 00:19:47,675
Reg, don't sweat it.
I'll take your place on the farm.

345
00:19:47,758 --> 00:19:49,807
Stop goofing, Andrews.

346
00:19:49,890 --> 00:19:51,103
You got other plans.

347
00:19:51,186 --> 00:19:52,941
Well, whatever I had planned,

348
00:19:53,025 --> 00:19:55,826
it's not as important
as getting you set up for college.

349
00:19:56,578 --> 00:19:57,790
And going pro.

350
00:19:58,584 --> 00:20:01,426
Besides, working the land with my hands?

351
00:20:01,970 --> 00:20:03,349
Giving back to the earth?

352
00:20:04,310 --> 00:20:06,817
And then writing about it
while leaned up against a haystack?

353
00:20:06,901 --> 00:20:11,332
I mean, that's exactly
what a Beat writer should be doing.

354
00:20:11,415 --> 00:20:13,296
My parents won't be able
to pay you, Archie.

355
00:20:13,923 --> 00:20:15,762
- And it's not easy work.
- Reg.

356
00:20:16,681 --> 00:20:17,518
I got it.

357
00:20:19,357 --> 00:20:20,736
It's all part of the experience.

358
00:20:21,696 --> 00:20:23,410
You're going to Camp Evans.

359
00:20:23,494 --> 00:20:25,625
Let me take up the slack at Duck Creek.

360
00:20:27,297 --> 00:20:31,434
Sleep in your barn, learn the ukulele,
break bread with your mom, your dad.

361
00:20:31,519 --> 00:20:33,525
[HEARTWARMING MUSIC PLAYING]

362
00:20:35,657 --> 00:20:36,492
Yeah.

363
00:20:36,994 --> 00:20:37,830
Okay.

364
00:20:39,251 --> 00:20:40,087
Sounds good.

365
00:20:43,974 --> 00:20:44,892
Thanks, Archie.

366
00:20:50,034 --> 00:20:51,038
I love you, Reg.

367
00:20:52,499 --> 00:20:53,754
I love you too, Archie.

368
00:21:04,371 --> 00:21:06,585
[CRYING QUIETLY]

369
00:21:06,669 --> 00:21:07,672
[BETTY] Mom?

370
00:21:10,472 --> 00:21:11,936
What is it? What's wrong?

371
00:21:12,938 --> 00:21:14,150
I, uh...

372
00:21:17,661 --> 00:21:19,458
I just finished your book.

373
00:21:22,300 --> 00:21:24,097
And I'm speechless.

374
00:21:25,978 --> 00:21:28,026
Well, I'm really glad that you read it.

375
00:21:29,322 --> 00:21:31,035
Betty, you wrote a book.

376
00:21:33,836 --> 00:21:35,549
A whole book.

377
00:21:35,632 --> 00:21:37,639
[EMOTIONAL MUSIC PLAYING]

378
00:21:39,227 --> 00:21:40,523
And you're right.

379
00:21:42,822 --> 00:21:44,494
I did get to know you better.

380
00:21:47,084 --> 00:21:48,380
And all those...

381
00:21:50,011 --> 00:21:54,525
wonderful, intelligent,
promising young women.

382
00:21:56,071 --> 00:22:01,380
So full of thoughts
and fears and struggles.

383
00:22:03,678 --> 00:22:05,015
And dreams.

384
00:22:08,610 --> 00:22:10,449
They have aspirations.

385
00:22:11,034 --> 00:22:12,539
Yeah. That's true.

386
00:22:15,005 --> 00:22:16,467
And then I think of myself,

387
00:22:16,551 --> 00:22:20,313
and my biggest dream
was being Miss Riverdale.

388
00:22:24,743 --> 00:22:27,627
Mom, you once told me
that you dreamed about being a stewardess.

389
00:22:27,711 --> 00:22:28,713
Mm.

390
00:22:28,796 --> 00:22:32,182
You wanted to see the world
and meet fascinating people

391
00:22:32,266 --> 00:22:34,439
and be a fascinating person.

392
00:22:35,610 --> 00:22:37,323
Yeah, well, that was a, uh...

393
00:22:38,744 --> 00:22:42,464
silly dream from a young girl
a long time ago.

394
00:22:42,548 --> 00:22:43,592
No, Mom.

395
00:22:47,354 --> 00:22:49,151
No dream is silly.

396
00:22:51,366 --> 00:22:55,086
I know you think
that it's too late for you, but it's not.

397
00:22:58,723 --> 00:23:00,394
You can be happy.

398
00:23:02,901 --> 00:23:04,449
Please, please...

399
00:23:05,368 --> 00:23:06,914
please believe that.

400
00:23:24,050 --> 00:23:28,064
[JUGHEAD] <i>Chances are, you won't ever see
this issue on a newsstand.</i>

401
00:23:28,648 --> 00:23:31,532
<i>Despite that, Pep Comics
has decided to release it.</i>

402
00:23:32,243 --> 00:23:36,046
<i>We are publishing this, our final issue,</i>

403
00:23:36,129 --> 00:23:39,097
<i>without the Comic Book Code
Seal of Approval.</i>

404
00:23:39,180 --> 00:23:43,736
<i>Most likely, that means this issue will
end up in either a landfill or a bonfire.</i>

405
00:23:43,820 --> 00:23:44,948
[FIRE ROARS]

406
00:23:45,031 --> 00:23:49,462
<i>But we here at Pep Comics refuse to kneel
to the un-American censorship</i>

407
00:23:49,546 --> 00:23:53,600
<i>that was specifically drafted
to silence stories like "The Comet."</i>

408
00:23:54,143 --> 00:23:57,445
<i>We hope that this comic book
will find its way into your hands.</i>

409
00:23:57,528 --> 00:24:00,203
<i>And, hopefully,
the stories in it will make you think.</i>

410
00:24:00,788 --> 00:24:02,711
<i>And make you feel a little less alone.</i>

411
00:24:03,881 --> 00:24:07,476
<i>So we at Pep Comics leave you
with this final message:</i>

412
00:24:07,559 --> 00:24:10,653
<i>It is easier to tear down
than to build up.</i>

413
00:24:11,237 --> 00:24:13,704
<i>Try to be a builder, not a destroyer.</i>

414
00:24:14,873 --> 00:24:18,092
<i>With that in mind, enjoy this
humble adaptation of "The Comet"</i>

415
00:24:18,176 --> 00:24:20,767
<i>by the great author W.E.B. Du Bois,</i>

416
00:24:20,850 --> 00:24:23,567
<i>a man who faced unthinkable adversity</i>

417
00:24:23,651 --> 00:24:25,866
<i>and still chose to believe
that the end of the world</i>

418
00:24:25,950 --> 00:24:28,709
<i>was not a foregone conclusion.</i>

419
00:24:29,335 --> 00:24:34,183
<i>There is always a chance
for a brighter, better, stronger future.</i>

420
00:24:35,145 --> 00:24:38,405
<i>From all of us at Pep Comics,
this is adieu...</i>

421
00:24:39,366 --> 00:24:40,536
<i>but not farewell.</i>

422
00:24:41,330 --> 00:24:42,585
<i>We'll meet again.</i>

423
00:24:43,462 --> 00:24:45,468
[GENTLE, STIRRING MUSIC PLAYING]

424
00:24:48,394 --> 00:24:49,313
Tabitha.

425
00:24:50,149 --> 00:24:53,075
- [DOOR CLOSES]
- Hi. What are you doing here?

426
00:24:53,158 --> 00:24:55,332
- Hi, stranger.
- Oh!

427
00:24:57,839 --> 00:24:59,470
Gee whiz.

428
00:24:59,553 --> 00:25:01,392
You're a sight for sore eyes.

429
00:25:03,273 --> 00:25:04,652
What happened to your glasses?

430
00:25:05,948 --> 00:25:07,870
And what's that television doing here?

431
00:25:09,501 --> 00:25:10,712
Jughead,

432
00:25:10,797 --> 00:25:16,565
I am not the Tabitha who's traveling
across the country with the NAACP.

433
00:25:17,901 --> 00:25:19,867
I'm the Tabitha that you've...

434
00:25:20,451 --> 00:25:21,579
forgotten.

435
00:25:22,708 --> 00:25:23,795
Uh...

436
00:25:24,380 --> 00:25:26,135
What are you talking about?

437
00:25:26,219 --> 00:25:27,096
Sit down.

438
00:25:28,392 --> 00:25:29,730
Let me show you something.

439
00:25:35,247 --> 00:25:38,632
- [INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING ON TV]
- [JUGHEAD ON TV] <i>Our story's about a town.</i>

440
00:25:38,715 --> 00:25:41,432
- Wowee. Is this a color television?
- [JUGHEAD] <i>A small town.</i>

441
00:25:41,515 --> 00:25:43,564
<i>And the people who live in the town.</i>

442
00:25:44,274 --> 00:25:47,200
<i>From a distance, it presents itself
like so many other small towns...</i>

443
00:25:47,283 --> 00:25:48,496
Is that my voice?

444
00:25:48,579 --> 00:25:51,421
<i>- ...all over the world. Safe.</i>
- Just absorb.

445
00:25:51,505 --> 00:25:52,676
<i>Decent. Innocent.</i>

446
00:25:52,759 --> 00:25:55,100
And then I will explain everything.

447
00:25:55,183 --> 00:25:59,237
[JUGHEAD] <i>Get closer, though, and you
start seeing the shadows underneath.</i>

448
00:25:59,320 --> 00:26:02,079
<i>The name of our town is Riverdale.</i>

449
00:26:03,082 --> 00:26:04,796
[SINGER ON TV] <i>♪ Tell me... ♪</i>

450
00:26:08,641 --> 00:26:09,477
[ANGEL TABITHA] Well?

451
00:26:14,158 --> 00:26:15,412
I remember.

452
00:26:15,495 --> 00:26:17,251
[EMOTIONAL MUSIC PLAYING]

453
00:26:18,003 --> 00:26:19,550
I remember everything.

454
00:26:21,180 --> 00:26:24,858
That I sent you and everyone back to 1955

455
00:26:24,941 --> 00:26:27,950
to save Riverdale from Bailey's Comet?

456
00:26:28,034 --> 00:26:30,626
And that,
while you and all of your friends worked

457
00:26:30,709 --> 00:26:34,262
to make this timeline less dark
and nihilistic and hopeless,

458
00:26:34,346 --> 00:26:37,396
I was trying to untangle
the various timelines

459
00:26:37,480 --> 00:26:39,151
that had gotten jumbled?

460
00:26:39,235 --> 00:26:41,493
Shore up the multiverse, in other words.

461
00:26:43,290 --> 00:26:44,669
We were successful?

462
00:26:45,672 --> 00:26:46,550
You were.

463
00:26:48,179 --> 00:26:49,434
You all did great.

464
00:26:49,517 --> 00:26:51,481
All of your collective innate decency,

465
00:26:51,565 --> 00:26:55,911
all of your struggles, have started
to reshape this town, this world.

466
00:26:56,496 --> 00:26:59,923
And it will just keep getting better
and better.

467
00:27:01,512 --> 00:27:02,933
Neat. [CHUCKLING]

468
00:27:04,188 --> 00:27:05,023
Awesome.

469
00:27:06,737 --> 00:27:10,875
I assume that you were successful too?

470
00:27:11,753 --> 00:27:13,842
After much trial and error,

471
00:27:13,926 --> 00:27:17,521
I realized it would be impossible
for me to untangle and...

472
00:27:17,604 --> 00:27:19,818
And pull apart
all of the various timelines,

473
00:27:19,903 --> 00:27:23,831
so, instead, I wove them all
into a single timeline.

474
00:27:24,792 --> 00:27:25,837
This one.

475
00:27:25,921 --> 00:27:28,931
And I used all of the energy
from all of the other timelines

476
00:27:29,014 --> 00:27:31,605
to stabilize it and fortify it.

477
00:27:32,985 --> 00:27:33,903
Great.

478
00:27:35,450 --> 00:27:36,370
It is.

479
00:27:37,331 --> 00:27:38,293
But, um...

